inent scholar Saikrishna Prakash offers the first truly comprehensive study of the original American presidency. Drawing from a vast range of sources both well known and obscure, this volume reconstructs the powers and duties of the nation’s chief executive at the Constitution’s founding. Among other subjects, Prakash examines the term and structure of the office of the president, as well as the president’s power as constitutional executor of the law, authority in foreign policy, role as commander in chief, level of control during emergencies, and relationship with the Congress, the courts, and the states. This ambitious and even-handed analysis counters numerous misconceptions about the presidency and fairly demonstrates that the office was seen as monarchical from its inception.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Mai 2023) 0aConstitutional historyzUnited States. 0aExecutive powerzUnited StatesxHistoryy18th century. 0aJudgeszUnited StatesxHistoryy18th century. 0aLegislative powerzUnited StatesxHistoryy18th century. 0aPolitical leadershipzUnited StatesxHistoryy18th century. 0aPresidentszUnited StatesxHistoryy18th century. 0aRepublicanismzUnited StatesxHistoryy18th century. 7aLAW / Constitutional.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertYale University Press Complete eBook-Package 2014-2015z97831106725030 cprintz978030019456240uhttps://doi.org/10.12987/978030021341640uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780300213416423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780300213416/original  a978-3-11-067250-3  Yale University Press Complete eBook-Package 2014-2015c2014d2015  aEBA_FAO  aEBA_UCA_YUP  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aZDB-23-UCY